## Safety & Security

[CUNY](/CUNY_Graduate_Center) maintains a unified [public safety department](/Public_safety_department), officially known as the [City University of New York Public Safety Department](/City_University_of_New_York_Public_Safety_Department), which operates distinct branches at each of the 26 [CUNY](/CUNY_Graduate_Center) campuses. This centralized structure aims to ensure a consistent approach to security across the vast university system.

It is important to note that the [New York City Police Department](/New_York_City_Police_Department) (NYPD) retains its role as the primary policing and investigation agency within [New York City](/New_York_City), as stipulated by the [NYC Charter](/New_York_City_Charter). This jurisdiction naturally extends to all [CUNY](/CUNY_Graduate_Center) campuses and facilities, meaning that while [CUNY](/CUNY_Graduate_Center) has its own public safety personnel, the [NYPD](/New_York_City_Police_Department) holds ultimate authority for serious criminal matters.

The Public Safety Department, however, has not been immune to criticism, particularly from student groups. A notable incident occurred on November 21, 2011, when several students protesting tuition increases attempted to occupy the lobby of [Baruch College](/Baruch_College). The occupiers were forcibly removed from the area, and several arrests were made, leading to considerable public scrutiny and renewed debates about the balance between student protest rights and institutional security protocols.

## Antisemitism at CUNY

In recent years, the issue of antisemitism on [CUNY](/CUNY_Graduate_Center) campuses has garnered significant attention, with a number of incidents being reported and documented.

*   In March 2014, [Brooklyn College](/Brooklyn_College) reached a settlement in a Title VI complaint that the Zionist Organization of America ("ZOA") had filed, alleging antisemitic discrimination within the institution.
*   In 2017, a [CUNY](/CUNY_Graduate_Center) administrator was controversially recorded stating that there were "too many Jews on campus," an incident that sparked widespread condemnation.
*   In 2020, a [CUNY](/CUNY_Graduate_Center) student was arrested for spray-painting antisemitic graffiti on a campus building, a disturbing act of hate speech.
*   A 2021 survey revealed a troubling statistic: nearly one in four [CUNY](/CUNY_Graduate_Center) students reported having experienced antisemitism on campus. The survey also indicated that Jewish students were more likely to report feeling unsafe on campus compared to students of other faiths, highlighting a significant concern for student well-being.
*   In May 2021, a student at [John Jay College of Criminal Justice](/John_Jay_College_of_Criminal_Justice) posted a picture of Adolf Hitler on Instagram accompanied by a message stating "We need another Hitler today." Following this egregious incident, a group of Jewish students met with Karol Mason, the President of the college, who, to the dismay of many, reportedly refused to publicly condemn the action.
*   The Equal Employment Opportunity Commission (EEOC) cited [CUNY](/CUNY_Graduate_Center) in 2021 for its failure to adequately protect a Jewish professor after the Professional Staff Congress (PSC) allegedly discriminated against him and subjected him to a hostile work environment on the basis of his Jewish faith, raising serious questions about institutional accountability.

In response to these escalating concerns, [CUNY](/CUNY_Graduate_Center) has publicly stated that it has taken steps to address antisemitism on its campuses. In 2020, the university established a dedicated task force to combat antisemitism. This task force has since developed a number of initiatives, including specialized training programs for faculty and staff on how to effectively identify and address antisemitism.

More recently, in June 2024, the [United States Department of Education](/United_States_Department_of_Education) concluded that [CUNY](/CUNY_Graduate_Center) had indeed failed to protect Jewish students from discrimination following the harrowing [October 7 attacks](/2023_Hamas-led_attack_on_Israel). [CUNY](/CUNY_Graduate_Center)'s [Hunter College](/Hunter_College) also faced particular scrutiny for incidents dating back to 2021. In response to these findings, Chancellor [Félix V. Matos Rodríguez](/F%C3%A9lix_V._Matos_Rodr%C3%ADguez) issued a statement affirming [CUNY](/CUNY_Graduate_Center)'s dedication to maintaining a discrimination-free and hate-free environment, and announced that new measures would be implemented to ensure consistent and transparent investigation and resolution of all complaints, a commitment that remains under close observation.

## City University Television (CUNY TV)

Beyond its academic and administrative functions, [CUNY](/CUNY_Graduate_Center) also operates its own broadcast television service, [CUNY TV](/CUNY_TV). Accessible on channel 75 for [Spectrum](/Spectrum_(cable_service)) subscribers and digital HD broadcast channel 25.3, [CUNY TV](/CUNY_TV) provides a diverse range of programming. This includes [telecourses](/Distance_learning) for distance learners, a curated selection of classic and foreign films, engaging magazine shows, and thoughtful panel discussions, often presented in various foreign languages, reflecting the rich linguistic diversity of [New York City](/New_York_City).

## City University Film Festival (CUNYFF)

The [City University Film Festival](/City_University_Film_Festival) (CUNYFF) serves as [CUNY](/CUNY_Graduate_Center)'s official showcase for cinematic talent. The festival, which was founded in 2009, provides a vital platform for student filmmakers and artists from across the university system to present their work, fostering creativity and collaboration within the diverse [CUNY](/CUNY_Graduate_Center) community.

## Notable alumni

The legacy of [CUNY](/CUNY_Graduate_Center) is perhaps most vividly illustrated through the achievements of its vast network of alumni. Graduates of the [City University of New York](/City_University_Of_New_York) include an astounding [13 Nobel laureates](/List_of_Nobel_laureates_affiliated_with_the_City_University_of_New_York), 2 [Fields Medalists](/Fields_Medal) (the highest honor in mathematics), 2 [U.S. Secretaries of State](/United_States_Secretary_of_State), a Supreme Court Justice, several [New York City](/New_York_City) mayors, numerous members of Congress and state legislators, groundbreaking scientists, influential artists, and even Olympians. This diverse array of accomplishments underscores the profound impact [CUNY](/CUNY_Graduate_Center) has had, and continues to have, on both local and global stages, a testament to the enduring power of accessible public education.

